        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "MOOC",
          "Succeeding in Subsequent Programming Task",
          "Succeed (1) vs Fail (0)",
          "328128 HOC4 learners, 152869 HOC18 learners",
          "HOC4, HOC8",
          "Perfect Solution for each task, Intermediate learner solutions in the poroblem-solving process",
          "[pathLength, currentPerf, AIScore]",
          "BKT, DKT or Additive Factor Model (AFM) struggle in contexts of data sparsity as is the case of informa programming contexts.\n\nMore specifically, if the dataset contains a small number of activities completed by each student.",
          "Authors present an Approaching Index - a measurement of similarity between current solution and ideal programming solution.\n\nThe proposed approach - Process Knowledge Tracing looks to model knowledge from the sequences of Approaching Indices when solving a question. In essence, the closer an intermediate solution\n\n",
          "Paths that do not lead to a solution have been disregarded. Same goes with duplicate solutions.\n\nAuthors create the approaching index (AI) as a measure of simialrity between learner’s current solution AND a pre-defined optimal solution. Similarity was computed using Tree-Edit Distance (TED)\n\nData was undersampled for Class rebalancing",
          "LR+pathLength, LR+currentPerf, PoissonPath, DKT-P, PKT-Variables, PKT-Sequences",
          "Holdout Method",
          "HOC4 to HOC5\n{Accuracy: 0.95958 - LR+currentPerf, Specificity: 0.6347 - PKT-Variables, Cohen’s Kappa: 0.064 - PoissonPath, AUC: 0.9807 - DKT-P}\n\nHOC18 to HOC19\n{Accuracy: 0.91296 - LR+currentPerf, Specificity: 0.69201 - DKT-P, Cohen’s Kappa: 0.317 - LR+currentPer, AUC: 0.9859 - PKT-Sequences}",
          "In programming tasks, reaching a solution can be thought of as following an Abstract Syntax tree (AST). From a root solution, there are multiple possible pathways a student can follow. The actual process a student follows is called a programming path. \n\n\n2 different models are attempted: \n\nPKT-Variables, which uses 3 features for a logistic regression.\n\nPKT-sequences, which uses the AI sequences along with path length and current performance.\n\nPKT-Sequences and PKT-variables achieved performances close to best-performing models, especially on the harder problems (HOC18 to HOC19).",
          "Limited number of tasks for evaluation.\n\nProblems tested had one and only one optimal solution. Model as designed REQ_UIRES an optimal solution.\n\nTED-Based similarity may not be ideal form of similarity ibetween programming tasks.\n\nNo Cross-Validation.\n\n\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 6
    }
  ],
